### “AI-ready datasets” from a ML training point of view 

Florian Pinault, ECMWF

Anemoi  
- Focused on ML based weather forecasting but support different users have different data, algorithms, grids, etc.  
- typically also all observations go through Anemoi / should go through Anemoi  
![][image1]  
- Getting data performance is not super essential for training task – as long as it doesn’t take months/years  
- Training data are often very customized, data need to be able to read very fast, data has to represent IO-pattern → one chuck= all data for a given reference data / given time window (training data is read many times during the training, with suffling). ECMWF target to have 0 GPU wait during the training  
![][image2]![][image3]

- Anemoi doesn’t support irregular data with single parameter since that’s a use case for Anemoi community  
![][image4]

- ECMWF still looking for the correct solution for this case

![][image5]

ECMWF plans to develop Anemoi interface for obs data:   
![][image6]  
Closer the dissemination data are to this logic easier it is to ingest to Anemoi

Discussion:   
- What is the best strategy to define chunks, i.e. with polar-orbiting satellites? --> still investigating. It might differ for data fitting to memory and data not fitting to memory.  
- Parquet provides nice tools to get statistics

### Accessing NWC SAF CF buckets with kerchunk, virtualizarr & icechunk

Jose Llorenç Lliso, NWC SAF

[Presentation](../zarr/presentations/icechunk_lessons.pdf)

Exercise done using NWC SAF output

![][image7]![][image8]

Lessons learned  
- Each element need to have one time dimensions important – not just attributes, here one file per one time used  
- Groups should be ok  
- The spatial dimensions should match  
- Icechunc provided better performance  
- Use parquet of big collections

What’s the difference of this and multifile datasets in xarray?  
- mfdatasets are much slower as they don't contain sufficient indexes
- performance of the presented use case hasn't been really tested yet

### Discussion 

Do you think it's realistic to provide training-ready datasets for e.g. satellite data which are generic enough for many enough users so that it makes sense? Is it easier to adapt data from this kind of prepared data than from native data?

- Releasing training-ready data would be good  
- Datasets need to be indexed, all use cases are different anyway. We should provide indexes so that users can pull out what they need. That should come with python code.  
- Satellite navigation information (e.g. applying satellite drifting) need to be done upstream, subsetting and combining parameters should be done by users. 

We have clouds in original projection? Is it reasonable to reproject on-fly or do we have to save?  
- re-projection alters values and it’s hard to guess the correct projection for each users
